[30;1m533 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m556 | [0m[35mAnother thing to be aware of when working with NumPy arrays is the datatype[0m
[30;1m557 | [0m[35mof the array. Some of the arrays (especially the mapped pixel type) often return[0m
[30;1m558 | [0m[35marrays with an unsigned 8-bit value. These arrays will easily overflow if you are[0m
[30;1m559 | [0m[35mnot careful. NumPy will use the same coercion that you find in C programs, so[0m
[30;1m560 | [0m[35mmixing an operation with 8-bit numbers and 32-bit numbers will give a result as[0m

[30;1m504 | [0m[35m      operate on many pixels at a time like with the blit, fill and draw[0m
[30;1m505 | [0m[35m      methods - or by using :mod:`pygame.surfarray`/:mod:`pygame.PixelArray`.[0m

[30;1m237 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m238 | [0m[35m   This will load a sound file and queue it. A queued sound file will begin as[0m
[30;1m239 | [0m[35m   soon as the current sound naturally ends. Only one sound can be queued at a[0m
[30;1m240 | [0m[35m   time. Queuing a new sound while another sound is queued will result in the[0m
[30;1m241 | [0m[35m   new sound becoming the queued sound. Also, if the current sound is ever[0m
[30;1m242 | [0m[35m   stopped or changed, the queued sound will be lost.[0m

[30;1m77 | [0m[35m   The area covered by a Rect does not include the right- and bottom-most edge[0m
[30;1m78 | [0m[35m   of pixels. If one Rect's bottom border is another Rect's top border (i.e.,[0m
[30;1m79 | [0m[35m   rect1.bottom=rect2.top), the two meet exactly on the screen but do not[0m
[30;1m80 | [0m[35m   overlap, and ``rect1.colliderect(rect2)`` returns false.[0m
[30;1m81 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m417 | [0m[35m   Since pygame 2.0, ``pygame.display.get_desktop_sizes()`` has taken over[0m
[30;1m418 | [0m[35m   some use cases from ``pygame.display.list_modes()``:[0m
[30;1m419 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m420 | [0m[35m   To find a suitable size for non-fullscreen windows, it is preferable to[0m
[30;1m421 | [0m[35m   use ``pygame.display.get_desktop_sizes()`` to get the size of the *current*[0m
[30;1m422 | [0m[35m   desktop, and to then choose a smaller window size. This way, the window is[0m
[30;1m423 | [0m[35m   guaranteed to fit, even when the monitor is configured to a lower resolution[0m

[30;1m121 | [0m[35mexplicit list (so that streaming is possible).[0m

[30;1m134 | [0m[35mwant to use it over straight alpha?[0m
[30;1m135 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m136 | [0m[35mThere are two main reasons - and the first is performance. As you saw in the two formulas above, the[0m
[30;1m137 | [0m[35mis one less mathematical operation to do at composition time with premultiplied alpha. Assuming you [0m
[30;1m138 | [0m[35mnot adjusting your alpha in real-time - and in most game development usages you won't be, that is on[0m
[30;1m139 | [0m[35mless operation to do per pixel which means, that on average your premultiplied alpha blits will be a[0m
[30;1m140 | [0m[35mlittle bit faster than your straight alpha blits.[0m

[30;1m267 | [0m[35mAnd that is about all you need to know about alpha compositing and the differences between straight[0m
[30;1m268 | [0m[35malpha and premultiplied alpha. If you do want to learn more, then `wikipedia has a nice long article[0m
[30;1m269 | [0m[35mfor further reading. <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alpha_compositing>`_[0m

[30;1m134 | [0m[35mwant to use it over straight alpha?[0m
[30;1m135 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m136 | [0m[35mThere are two main reasons - and the first is performance. As you saw in the two formulas above, the[0m
[30;1m137 | [0m[35mis one less mathematical operation to do at composition time with premultiplied alpha. Assuming you [0m
[30;1m138 | [0m[35mnot adjusting your alpha in real-time - and in most game development usages you won't be, that is on[0m
[30;1m139 | [0m[35mless operation to do per pixel which means, that on average your premultiplied alpha blits will be a[0m
[30;1m140 | [0m[35mlittle bit faster than your straight alpha blits.[0m

[30;1m85 | [0m[35m'display surface' with ``pygame.display.set_mode()``.  You can create a surface[0m

[30;1m87 | [0m[35mthat contains text with :func:`pygame.font.Font.render()`.  You can even create a surface that[0m
[30;1m88 | [0m[35mcontains nothing at all with :func:`pygame.Surface()`.[0m
[30;1m89 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m90 | [0m[35mMost of the surface functions are not critical. Just learn :meth:`.Surface.blit()`,[0m
[30;1m91 | [0m[35m:meth:`.Surface.fill()`, :meth:`.Surface.set_at()` and :meth:`.Surface.get_at()`, and you'll be fine[0m

[30;1m342 | [0m[35mA note about ``event.poll()`` vs. ``wait()`` -- ``poll()`` may seem better,[0m
[30;1m343 | [0m[35msince it doesn't block your program from doing anything while it's waiting for[0m
[30;1m344 | [0m[35minput -- ``wait()`` suspends the program until an event is received.[0m
[30;1m345 | [0m[35mHowever, ``poll()`` will consume 100% of available CPU time while it runs,[0m
[30;1m346 | [0m[35mand it will fill the event queue with ``NOEVENTS``.  Use ``set_blocked()`` to[0m
[30;1m347 | [0m[35mselect just those event types you're interested in -- your queue will be much[0m
[30;1m348 | [0m[35mmore manageable.[0m

[30;1m33 | [0m[35mThe groups are designed for high efficiency in removing and adding Sprites to[0m
[30;1m34 | [0m[35mthem. They also allow cheap testing to see if a Sprite already exists in a[0m
[30;1m35 | [0m[35mGroup. A given Sprite can exist in any number of groups. A game could use some[0m
[30;1m36 | [0m[35mgroups to control object rendering, and a completely separate set of groups to[0m
[30;1m37 | [0m[35mcontrol interaction or player movement. Instead of adding type attributes or[0m
[30;1m38 | [0m[35mbools to a derived Sprite class, consider keeping the Sprites inside organized[0m
[30;1m39 | [0m[35mGroups. This will allow for easier lookup later in the game.[0m
[30;1m40 | [0m[35m[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m1693[0m[34m of [0m[33m1988[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000600[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.LOLBAS.Windows[0m

[30;1m33 | [0m[35mThe groups are designed for high efficiency in removing and adding Sprites to[0m
[30;1m34 | [0m[35mthem. They also allow cheap testing to see if a Sprite already exists in a[0m
[30;1m35 | [0m[35mGroup. A given Sprite can exist in any number of groups. A game could use some[0m
[30;1m36 | [0m[35mgroups to control object rendering, and a completely separate set of groups to[0m
[30;1m37 | [0m[35mcontrol interaction or player movement. Instead of adding type attributes or[0m
[30;1m38 | [0m[35mbools to a derived Sprite class, consider keeping the Sprites inside organized[0m
[30;1m39 | [0m[35mGroups. This will allow for easier lookup later in the game.[0m
